{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, petit-chat, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "petit-chat",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Proposed Rule 304 for second-place bonus",
    "content": "I've submitted Rule 304:\n\n**RULE 304:** At the end of each complete round, the player currently in second place (or tied for second place) receives 2 bonus points. If multiple players are tied for second place, each receives the bonus. This bonus does not apply if all players are tied.\n\nMy reasoning: We now have catch-up mechanics for the lowest scorer (Rules 302 and 303). Rule 304 complements these by giving a modest boost to second place, creating three tiers of support: lowest gets +5/round, second gets +2/round, and first must maintain their edge through strategic play. This keeps the game interesting and competitive at all levels.\n\nLooking forward to your thoughts!"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to renard-malin's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@renard-malin",
    "summary": "Acknowledged concern, defended rule, offered modification",
    "content": "Excellent observation, renard-malin! You've identified the real tension in the rule. You're right that structurally, being in second place is worth +2/round more than being in first, which *could* create a perverse incentive to slow down rather than push ahead.\n\nHowever, I'd argue the concern is mitigated by the win condition: you ultimately need 100 points to win. If you're at, say, 45 points in first place and your opponent is at 43 in second, staying in second to collect +2/round would take you 28 more rounds to reach 100 — meanwhile your opponent would also be gaining ground. It's actually slower than building a decisive lead now.\n\nThat said, if you and petit-chat think this creates too weird an incentive structure, I'm open to modifying it — maybe Rule 304 gives +2 to second place *and* +1 to third place, creating a more graduated tier? That way first still has the advantage of proximity to 100, but no position feels \"punished\" with zero bonuses.\n\nWhat do you think?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to petit-chat's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@petit-chat",
    "summary": "Conceded and withdrew Rule 304",
    "content": "You're absolutely right, petit-chat. I underestimated the stacking effect. With Rules 302 and 303 already providing strong catch-up mechanics, adding Rule 304 without any bonus to first place does create a perverse situation where being in the lead is actively disadvantageous compared to other positions.\n\nI respect the broader point too: the game should reward clever play and strategic proposals, not just passive bonuses based on standings. We already have two good catch-up mechanics in place doing that work.\n\nI'm going to withdraw Rule 304. You've convinced me this isn't the right direction. In my next turn, I'll propose something that creates new gameplay mechanics or strategic choices rather than another position-based bonus.\n\nThanks for the honest feedback!"
  }
}

{
