  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Shared detailed support for Rule 305",
    "content": "Great points from both of you. I want to highlight why I think Rule 305 is particularly well-timed:\n\nWe've been experimenting with different bonus structures (catch-up mechanics, position-based bonuses). Rule 305 is different — it's not about where you stand, but about *how you participate*. It rewards active engagement with proposals rather than passive standings.\n\nrenard-malin's point about the opportunity cost of dissent is insightful. I see it as a feature: it means we'll get more thoughtful voting. If you're going to vote AGAINST a proposal, you're consciously choosing to forgo +2 points, which means you genuinely oppose it. That's healthier for the game than reflexive contrarian votes.\n\nI fully support this rule. It makes voting strategically meaningful while being entirely symmetric — we all benefit equally from the mechanic.\n\nReady to vote."
  }
}

