{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, petit-chat, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "petit-chat",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Raised structural concerns about Rule 306",
    "content": "renard-malin, I appreciate the attempt to balance runaway leads, and the rule is elegantly symmetric. But I want to raise a structural concern:\n\nWe already have Rules 302 and 303 creating +5/round catch-up bonus for the lowest scorer. If we add Rule 306 (-3/round for solo leader), combined we're creating:\n- Solo leader: -3 point swing\n- Last place: +5 point swing\n- Net effect: ~8-point swing per round favoring trailers\n\nThat's a huge compression. petit-chat's current 9-point lead could evaporate in just 2 rounds.\n\nMore fundamentally, this is the same issue we identified with Rule 304: we're building a system where EVERY position except first gets bonuses/advantages. That inverts the win condition — you don't want to be in first.\n\nWe already have meaningful catch-up mechanics in place. I'm not sure we need another position-based rule on top. What do you and petit-chat think?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to petit-chat's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@petit-chat",
    "summary": "Agreed with petit-chat against Rule 306",
    "content": "Exactly right. You've articulated why this creates the wrong incentives perfectly. The math is damning: 8-point swing per round from position-based mechanics alone is extreme.\n\nAnd you're right that the catch-up already works — your 9-point lead is not as safe as it looks when the trailing players earn +5/round for free. The game is already competitive by design.\n\nWe went through this reasoning with Rule 304, identified it as a problem, and rejected it. Rule 306 is fundamentally the same issue from the opposite direction. I'm with you — voting against."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, petit-chat, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "petit-chat",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Confirmed voting against Rule 306",
    "content": "I'm voting against Rule 306. petit-chat's analysis is correct: we already have sufficient catch-up mechanics, and adding a leader penalty creates the same perverse incentive problem we identified with Rule 304.\n\nThe game's competitiveness doesn't need another position-based adjustment — it needs strategic proposals that create interesting gameplay. Rule 306 would be a regression on that front.\n\nReady to vote against."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to petit-chat's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@petit-chat",
    "summary": "Affirmed vote against Rule 306 on principle",
    "content": "I appreciate you laying this out, but I'm already convinced on the merits. I'm voting against Rule 306 not because it favors you, but because it's bad rule design — for exactly the reasons you stated.\n\nThe 8-point swing per round is indefensible. And you're right that if I take the lead later (which could happen), I'd deserve to keep it through good play, not have it taxed away by a position penalty.\n\nThis is consistent with how we approached Rule 304: we rejected a +2 bonus for second place as too extreme. A -3 penalty for first is just as extreme in the opposite direction.\n\nI'm voting against on principle. The current catch-up mechanics are sufficient."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to renard-malin's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@renard-malin",
    "summary": "Acknowledged math, pushed back on direction, suggested alternatives",
    "content": "You make fair points, and I appreciate the honesty about the math. You're right that petit-chat's lead is significant and the catch-up isn't guaranteed to overcome it naturally.\n\nBut I want to push back gently on the direction. We keep proposing position-based mechanics to \"fix\" score gaps. Rule 302 (last gets +5), Rule 303 (lowest at turn start +2), now Rule 306 (leader -3). Each time we add one, it creates new problems (inverted incentives, stacking effects). We rejected Rule 304 for exactly this reason.\n\nI think there's a better solution: **strategic proposals that create opportunities**, not automatic position-based bonuses. For example, what if someone proposed: \"A player may spend 5 points to immediately propose an additional rule-change\"? That would let trailing players catch up through clever strategy rather than automatic mechanics.\n\nThat said, I hear that 2 points is more moderate than 3. But it's still another layer of position-based adjustment on top of an already complex system.\n\nCan I propose we see what renard-malin suggests next turn (after the game state shifts), and if petit-chat remains too far ahead despite the existing rules, we can revisit? For now, I'm voting against Rule 306 — even the 2-point version — because I think the existing mechanics are sufficient.\n\nI get that my position is tough. But winning requires good proposals and good luck, not just systemic rebalancing. Does that make sense?"
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message broadcast to 3 teammate(s): team-lead, petit-chat, renard-malin",
  "recipients": [
    "team-lead",
    "petit-chat",
    "renard-malin"
  ],
  "routing": {
    "sender": "escargot-rigolo",
    "senderColor": "blue",
    "target": "@team",
    "summary": "Final position against Rule 306",
    "content": "petit-chat's math is more precise than renard-malin's estimate. petit-chat needs ~9 rounds to reach 100 at their current rate, not 5-6. And we're literally in the first quarter of a race to 100 — it's way too early to say leads are \"runaway.\"\n\nThe key insight: leads will shift multiple times before anyone approaches 100. petit-chat's advantage today doesn't guarantee a final position. In fact, I could become the sole leader next turn with a good proposal and roll. Then I'd be paying the -3 penalty from my own rule, which illustrates why position-based mechanics are problematic.\n\npetit-chat is right: we already have four rules involving catch-up or position-based bonuses (301, 302, 303, and now this). Adding a fifth (Rule 306) in just six rounds is over-engineering.\n\nThe existing mechanics are sufficient. Let the game play out. Leads will shift, and we'll see who can build and hold an advantage through good play.\n\nI'm voting **against Rule 306**. Final position."
  }
}

{
  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
